MORE (Multi-Omics REgulation) is an R package which is designed to infer condition-specific multi-omic regulatory networks. Developed by the BiostatOmics Lab, it is publicly available on the [BiostatOmics GitHub repository](https://github.com/BiostatOmics/MORE/). 

MORE uses either Multiple Linear Regression (MLR) or Partial Least Squares (PLS) to model the expression of the features of a target omic as a function of experimental variables (e.g., disease or treatment) and the target feature's potential regulators. For MLR, it applies advanced variable selection techniques such as ElasticNet or Iterative Sparse Group Lasso, while for PLS, it uses Jack-Knife or Permutation techniques in combination with the Variable Importance in Projection (VIP) to identify the significant regulators of the target omic feature expression in the biological system under study. Additionally, MORE can incorporate prior regulatory knowledge and clinical data.

# Installation

Currently, the package can be directly installed from GitHub using the `devtools` R package by:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("BiostatOmics/MORE")
```

For a more comprehensive overview of MORE functionalities, refer to the User Guide available [here](https://github.com/BiostatOmics/MORE/blob/main/vignettes/UsersGuide.pdf). 

For further information on the methodological details, please read the paper [paper](https://doi.org/10.1093/bib/bbaf270).  

# Load MORE

```{r}
library(MORE)
```

# Data {.tabset}

In this tutorial, we will use the [STATegra](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41597-019-0202-7) dataset, available [HERE](https://github.com/BiostatOmics/STATegra_data). A reduced version of this data is included in MORE as example data.

The STATegra dataset contains time-series data for pre-B-cell differentiation in mice, including six time points (0h, 2h, 6h, 12h, 18h, 24h). A set of samples has been subjected to drug-controlled induction of the Ikaros transcription factor, while the Control cells have not and, therefore, will not differentiate into B-cells.

First, load the data as follows:

```{r}
load('DataSTATegra.RData')
```

DataSTATegra loads the following objects: 

* `GeneExpressionDE`: RNA-seq data. Matrix with differentially expressed genes across conditions in rows and samples in columns.

* `data.omics`: List including each of the regulatory omics of the RNA-seq. Each omic is included in the list as a matrix with regulators in rows and samples in columns

* `associations`:  List containing pairs of gene-regulator known to interact, based on the literature and/or databases. 

* `edesign`: Matrix including the experimental design for each sample.

**Important:** MORE requires that the GeneExpression matrix and all matrices of the regulatory omics contain data from the same samples and in the same order. If sample labels differ, MORE will assume that samples are in the same order. 

Below, we preview each object to demonstrate how to format input data for MORE.

