## MLR + ISGL

To run MORE with Iterative Sparse Group Lasso variable selection, we would run:

```{r,eval=FALSE}

MLRISGLmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'ISGL',
                groupingISGL = 'MF_0.7',
                method = 'MLR')

```

As shown, we slightly changed the main function's parameters. In this case, we used `groupingISGL` instead of `alfaEN` to change from the EN alfa mixing parameter to the type of approach to consider when creating the groups in the ISGL. In this example, we used the multicollinearity approach (MF) with a correlation threshold of 0.7 to make the groups. Other options:

* `MF_X`: Takes the same approach as in the multicollinearity filter. Grouping the variables which correlate more than X.
* `PCA_X`: Extracts as many PCA components to explain X percent of the variability of the data and assigns the variables to the component in which they had the highest loadings. 


## PLS1 + Jack + VIP

To run MORE with Partial Least Squares (PLS), we slightly change the parameters of the main function. In this case, we use `alfa` instead of `alfaEN` to change from EN alfa mixing parameter to alpha (I type error) threshold to consider a p-value significant. 

In the case of PLS models, we will refer to significant regulators rather than relevant regulators. So outputs like `ResultsPerTargetF$relevantRegulators` change to outputs like `ResultsPerTargetF$significantRegulators`.

To run a PLS model with Jack-Knife as variable selection technique, we can run:

```{r,eval=FALSE}

PLSJackmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Jack',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

```

## PLS1 + Perm + VIP

To run a PLS model with Permutation as variable selection technique, we can run:

```{r,eval=FALSE}

PLS1model = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

```

## PLS2

All the above-presented models compute a unique model for each gene considered. However, when there is no prior regulatory knowledge, it could be beneficial to run a PLS2, which creates a unique model for all the genes. To do so, we run:

```{r,eval=FALSE}

PLS2mmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS2')

```

# Interpreting MORE results

We will use the results from the PLS model with Jack-Knife variable selection to demonstrate the various functionalities that MORE incorporates.

First, we run the `RegulationPerCondition()` function, which returns a summary of the significant regulations for each gene. We can load the pre-computed results to avoid excessive runtime:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
regpcond = RegulationPerCondition(PLSJackmodel)
```
```{r, echo=FALSE, include=FALSE}
load('PLSJackmodel.Rdata')
```

```{r}
load('RegulationperConditionPLS.RData')
```

```{r}
head(regpcond)
```

Looking at the results of `regpcond`, remember that `Group_0` and `Group_1` correspond to the Control and Ikaros conditions, respectively (as codified in `edesign`). The condition-specific coefficients can be interpreted as follows:

* If two experimental groups have the same coefficients, the regulator has the same effect on the gene in both conditions.

* If the coefficient is 0 in one of the groups, the regulator has no effect on the gene under that condition. 

* Experimental conditions with different, non-zero coefficients indicate that the regulator affects the gene in these conditions, but the magnitude of the effect is not the same for the groups.

```{r, eval=FALSE}
regpcondMLR = RegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel)
```

```{r,echo=FALSE, include=FALSE}
load('RegulationperCondition.RData')
regpcondMLR = regpcond
load('RegulationperConditionPLS.RData')
```

We will also show the output of running the same function to the output of an MLR model with ElasticNet variable selection so that the user can see how information about multicollinearity is added to this output.

```{r}
head(regpcondMLR)
```

To further explore the results of MORE, we can start with some summary plots of the computed models. 

The `summaryPlot` function represents the percentage of genes with relevant regulations and the percentage of regulations found to be relevant in each omic, depending on whether the `bytargetF` parameter is set to TRUE or FALSE. We can also stratify the results by filtering by $R^2$, e.g. see the percentage of genes for which the model explains at least 90% of the variance:

```{r}
summaryPlot(PLSJackmodel, regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)
```

```{r}
summaryPlot(PLSJackmodel, regpcond, byTargetF = FALSE, filterR2 = 0.9)
```

Notice that transcription factors account for the majority of regulatory relationships and that, when looking at the percentage of regulations, all omic layers have more relevant regulations in the Ikaros condition, indicative of the activation of the gene regulation machinery as a result of the action of this transcription factor.

After this prior study, if one is interested in focusing their efforts on analyzing the regulatory networks of a subset of genes that were better modelled by MORE, they can use `filterR2` to do so.

To create smaller regulatory networks, we will apply the filter previously used in this example ($R^2>0.9$).

In MORE, there are two ways to obtain the subset of genes that showed an $R^2$ above the one the user wants to consider. The first is:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
regpcond_filtered = RegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel, filterR2 = 0.9)
```

However, in the cases where MORE found a high amount of significant regulations this can be very time-consuming. So we recommend using this second option specially designed to apply the filter:

```{r}
regpcond_filtered = FilterRegulationPerCondition(output = PLSJackmodel, outputRegpcond = regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)
```

To explore the differential regulators across experimental conditions and omics, MORE incorporates the `differentialRegPlot()` function. It can be applied either to the full set of genes or to those filtered by the $R^2$. In our case, we will apply it to the filtered subset of genes, as we will focus our efforts on analyzing the results for these specific genes. This plot can be easily obtained by:

```{r}
differentialRegPlot(output = PLSJackmodel, outputRegpcond = regpcond_filtered)
```

This plot helps us explore the proportion of significant regulators that are shared in the analyzed conditions and the proportion of condition-specific significant regulators by the regulatory omics.

MORE also provides visualization functions to explore gene-regulator relationships for the pairs identified as significant by MORE. 

When no specific regulator is provided, a plot is generated for each gene, displaying all its significant regulators along with the gene’s expression pattern. 

To also show how these plots could help us verify the correlated patterns of the regulators detected by MORE, we will create those plots for the MLR with the ElasticNet models' output.

Since our example gene has many relevant regulators, we will show the regulatory patterns of the Foxo1 TF, which is representative of the mc1_1 group of correlated regulators. In this group, the Gtf2b TF and the mmu-miR-1187 miRNA are positively and negatively correlated regulators with Foxo1, respectively. This results can be observed looking at the expected activation/repression regulatory patterns:

```{r, fig.show='hold', out.width='50%'}
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Foxo1", order = TRUE, size = 6)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Gtf2b", order = TRUE, size = 6)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "mmu-miR-1187",  order = TRUE, size = 6)
```

When more than 50 observations are considered in the data to be analyzed, identifying patterns becomes difficult. For that reason, to simplify the exploration of the patterns, observations are ordered so that their target feature expression is shown in an ascending way; this is easily done by `order = TRUE`. However, in this specific case, as the dataset contains observations that have been measured also in different data points, exploring those patterns without taking into account this temporality makes no sense. For this reason, in this case, these plots should be re-explored in the following way:

```{r, fig.show='hold', out.width='50%'}
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Foxo1", order = FALSE, size = 6)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Gtf2b", order = FALSE, size = 6)

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "mmu-miR-1187",  order = FALSE, size = 6)
```


Additionally, if a regulator is specified but no gene is provided, MORE will generate plots for all gene–regulator pairs in which that regulator was identified as significant. Let’s do this for miRNA mmu-miR-146a-5p, a miRNA that regulates 4 genes according to the MORE results:

```{r, fig.show='hold', out.width='50%'}
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = NULL, regulator = "mmu-miR-146a-5p", order = FALSE)
```

If the relationship between the gene and the regulator is difficult to discern in those plots, we can simplify them and try to see them in a scatterplot. Re-using the previous example:

```{r}
plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078", regulator = "Foxo1", simplify =  TRUE)
```

Returning to the results of the PLS model, we can explore the Scores and Weight Plots trying to better understand which regulators co-act, their relation to the gene we are analyzing, and the relation of the conditions with the target feature and the regulators.

```{r, fig.show='hold', out.width='50%'}
plotScores(PLSJackmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078")
plotWeight(PLSJackmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000078")
```

Looking at the Score plot, first it can be seen how there is not a clear separation between the conditions in the different dimension. Other dimensions should be explored to see if there is any dimension that could explain better the differences across conditions. Looking at the labels, it can not be seen differences according to the different batches. However, looking at the time points it can be seen some aggrupation of the different time points. According to this results, it would be a good idea to take into account this time points in the experimental design when creating the MORE models or correcting the batch effect previous to creating the models.

Looking at the Weights plot, we can see how a group of TFs co-act together (some of them include Zfp775, Hivep2, Foxo1, Myb, Mef2d, Arid5a,...) there are other groups that can be detected as the pair mmu-miR-3074-1-3p, mmu-miR-466n-3p and others but we won't list all of them. We can also see that in this dimensions we could expect a positive relationship between the regulators of the first group listed and the ENSMUSG00000000078 gene. However, it is important to analyze the rest of the dimensions to have a better idea of the whole model.

Additionally, in MORE, we can easily visualize the regulatory networks inferred by MORE using the following code:

```{r}
networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = FALSE)
```

Since these networks can be complex to analyze directly in R, MORE includes an extension to export them for interactive exploration in Cytoscape. To enable this, Cytoscape **MUST** be open and operative before executing:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = TRUE)
```

This code creates the following networks:

